From c2823a6f5ca1fd19fbe8ef227c4712dcf1091599 Mon Sep 17 00:00:00 2001
From: Daniel Golle <daniel@makrotopia.org>
Date: Sun, 15 Feb 2026 18:36:14 +0000
Subject: [PATCH 07/26] boot: add imagemap on-demand loading abstraction

Introduce struct imagemap, a small generic layer that lets callers
read arbitrary byte ranges from a storage device and keeps a
translation table of the regions that have already been loaded into
RAM.

A read-callback plus an opaque *priv pointer abstract the actual I/O
so that block, MTD, and UBI back-ends can be added in follow-up
patches without touching the core.

Each backend provides a .cleanup callback which is invoked to release
held device references and free allocated memory. This ensures safe
resource teardown between consecutive boot attempts.

The translation table avoids redundant reads when the same region is
requested more than once, and allows extending an existing mapping
when a larger size is needed at the same offset. Mapped regions which
are not at a caller-supplied address are allocated using the LMB
allocator and released automatically on cleanup.

Signed-off-by: Daniel Golle <daniel@makrotopia.org>
---
Changes since RFC:
  - Renamed image_loader to imagemap throughout (Simon)
  - Imagemap backends are now proper drivers with the storage device as
    parent, similar to bootdev drivers (Simon)
  - Use lmb allocator for mapped regions instead of open-coded bump
    allocator; lmb_free on cleanup (Tom)
  - Return ERR_PTR on map/map_to failure instead of NULL
  - Overflow-safe range check in imagemap_lookup() to prevent unsigned
    underflow on LP64
  - lmb_free on failed extend-read to avoid leaking reservations
  - NULL checks on strdup
---
